00:09:48,465 --> 00:09:51,246
And if we look at Facebook in 2020, this is sort of...

128
00:09:53,525 --> 00:09:58,529
an excerpt from one tier of Facebook's hate speech rules.

129
00:10:00,610 --> 00:10:04,252
It is a portion of tier one of their hate speech rules,

130
00:10:04,292 --> 00:10:05,813
which is divided into three tiers.

131
00:10:06,173 --> 00:10:08,535
And this is one form of behavior, right?

132
00:10:08,915 --> 00:10:11,837
And I'm not saying that Facebook is the example here, right?

133
00:10:11,917 --> 00:10:14,199
They have a lot of problems,

134
00:10:14,699 --> 00:10:19,442
but I think if we look between their 2006 rules,

135
00:10:19,502 --> 00:10:21,603
which lumped all of these things into one,

136
00:10:22,865 --> 00:10:36,054
And we look at 2020, we can see the degree to which they've been faced with a variety of different kinds of behavior and had to adapt their rules to address these kinds of behaviors on their service.

137
00:10:37,275 --> 00:10:46,901
And we can see a similar kind of comparison. If we look at Fortnite in 2020, we have these sort of lumps of different kinds of content all put in one rule.

138
00:10:47,342 --> 00:10:50,243
And again, if we look at Twitter in 2006, right, we have a very similar.

139
00:10:52,318 --> 00:10:53,498
kind of lumping the rules.

140
00:10:54,199 --> 00:10:58,880
And Twitter has also sort of in the past 10 years or so,

141
00:11:00,121 --> 00:11:00,621
14 years or so,

142
00:11:00,641 --> 00:11:08,224
and made their policies and the rule more granular over time.

143
00:11:08,744 --> 00:11:11,766
And so if we think about Facebook and Twitter in 2006

144
00:11:11,806 --> 00:11:13,867
and where they were, right?

145
00:11:14,947 --> 00:11:17,268
That was the point at which Facebook was going

146
00:11:17,408 --> 00:11:20,189
from being a service that was purely for college students

147
00:11:20,289 --> 00:11:21,550
to a more open market.

148
00:11:22,499 --> 00:11:30,906
That was a point at which, you know, the press was sort of marveling at Twitter and this sort of new incarnation of microblog, right?

149
00:11:32,107 --> 00:11:46,397
I don't think anyone writing or working there was thinking that 10 years from this point, one of the main discussions of the 2016 US presidential election is going to be focused on these two services, right?

