00:11:57,845 --> 00:11:59,306
They just weren't seeing that.

154
00:11:59,347 --> 00:12:01,248
They didn't have the benefit of hindsight.

155
00:12:01,808 --> 00:12:05,351
And so that's what I'm hoping to provide a little bit here

156
00:12:05,471 --> 00:12:07,873
for the game industry and for online games,

157
00:12:08,393 --> 00:12:11,436
to look at, OK, what did social media do?

158
00:12:11,776 --> 00:12:13,577
What is the hindsight lessons that

159
00:12:13,597 --> 00:12:16,119
can be learned from how social media has

160
00:12:16,199 --> 00:12:18,081
failed over the last 10 years?

161
00:12:18,451 --> 00:12:21,652
that can then be adapted to online games as we move forward.

162
00:12:22,132 --> 00:12:25,013
So I'm gonna divide this into three sort of big failures

163
00:12:25,173 --> 00:12:27,133
as we see them for social media.

164
00:12:28,353 --> 00:12:31,534
One is that social media was designed for scale

165
00:12:31,774 --> 00:12:35,895
and engagement first without centering the safety of users,

166
00:12:35,995 --> 00:12:39,256
especially for vulnerable and marginalized communities.

167
00:12:39,316 --> 00:12:41,397
So the motto of Facebook at its outset

168
00:12:41,417 --> 00:12:44,397
was move fast and break things.

169
00:12:44,437 --> 00:12:46,658
One of the big quotes from Twitter,

170
00:12:47,165 --> 00:12:48,565
over their lifetime, I think this was from 2012,

171
00:12:48,885 --> 00:12:53,527
was that we are the free speech wing of the free speech party.

172
00:12:53,927 --> 00:12:57,749
So these are mantras and ideologies

173
00:12:58,089 --> 00:13:02,890
that are centering the mass expansion of these platforms,

174
00:13:03,310 --> 00:13:06,392
the engagement of users, and is not really thinking about,

175
00:13:06,492 --> 00:13:09,293
OK, when we talk about free speech,

176
00:13:10,773 --> 00:13:13,574
how are we thinking about the impact of speech?

177
00:13:13,914 --> 00:13:15,575
When we're talking about breaking things,

178
00:13:15,835 --> 00:13:16,715
are we talking about?

179
00:13:17,310 --> 00:13:23,171
Are we talking about the experience of targets of harassment?

180
00:13:23,331 --> 00:13:32,093
Do we feel comfortable breaking the society that we are a part of?

181
00:13:32,153 --> 00:13:34,894
I don't think these sort of large questions were being asked.

182
00:13:35,014 --> 00:13:42,255
So for the game industry, we would recommend that they take responsibility for the experience

183
00:13:42,435 --> 00:13:43,636
of players and incorporate

184
00:13:45,077 --> 00:13:49,959
anti hate by design principles when creating online games. So this is just a small example.

185
00:13:50,299 --> 00:13:56,261
When you're designing a new game or when you're changing an existing game, think about these

186
00:13:56,441 --> 00:14:02,484
couple of questions. What are the speech implications of design and policy choices in

187
00:14:02,504 --> 00:14:08,227
your game? Whose speech will be most impacted by the choices that you're making? If you're trying

188
00:14:08,247 --> 00:14:11,748
to address a disruptive behavior in an online game.

189
00:14:13,666 --> 00:14:15,627
Is it best addressed through changing a product?

190
00:14:16,207 --> 00:14:18,748
Is there a form of community moderation,

191
00:14:19,288 --> 00:14:23,250
empowering users to enact the norms of the community

192
00:14:23,770 --> 00:14:25,310
that you can work toward?

193
00:14:25,771 --> 00:14:28,952
Or is there a need for a real global policy

194
00:14:29,312 --> 00:14:31,393
that will state both for users and for the public

195
00:14:31,413 --> 00:14:34,114
that this kind of behavior or these kinds of ideologies

196
00:14:34,174 --> 00:14:36,355
are not welcome on our service?

197
00:14:36,915 --> 00:14:38,436
And how do you go about resourcing

198
00:14:38,836 --> 00:14:41,117
each of those different approaches?

199
00:14:42,032 --> 00:14:46,776
And third, I'll say, what kind of research would be valuable as you are building these,

200
00:14:49,278 --> 00:14:55,003
your game platform or changing your game? Who's doing that research? How can you connect with

201
00:14:55,063 --> 00:15:02,970
them? Making sure that all of your design and policy and moderation decisions are informed

202
00:15:03,330 --> 00:15:08,975
by research that either you are finding or that even potentially that you are initiating and

203
00:15:09,215 --> 00:15:09,936
conducting yourself?

204
00:15:12,334 --> 00:15:17,577
So failure number two of social media is changes as crisis PR.

205
00:15:17,597 --> 00:15:20,899
So we had these platforms that were built for scale and engagement.

206
00:15:21,499 --> 00:15:25,582
And when we see the real world impact of these of these systems,

207
00:15:26,462 --> 00:15:30,284
despite calls from ADL and other organizations over the years to change,

208
00:15:30,805 --> 00:15:35,107
the time where we see real change on these platforms is in response

209
00:15:35,327 --> 00:15:40,250
to real life tragedies that cost human life.

210
00:15:40,430 --> 00:15:40,570
So.

211
00:15:42,233 --> 00:15:43,234
There's three examples here.

212
00:15:43,354 --> 00:15:46,457
One is in Charlottesville, Virginia in 2017.

213
00:15:47,257 --> 00:15:50,560
So ADL and other organizations had been telling

214
00:15:50,600 --> 00:15:52,041
social media companies about the threat

215
00:15:52,061 --> 00:15:55,704
of white supremacy for many years

216
00:15:56,364 --> 00:15:57,805
and asking them to take it more seriously

217
00:15:57,825 --> 00:15:58,606
and take more steps.

218
00:15:59,086 --> 00:16:02,889
But it was only when extremists got together

219
00:16:03,009 --> 00:16:07,373
